    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>LEAD: To the Editor:</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>LEAD: To the Editor:</p>
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>I must respond to innacurate statements in your Nov. 23 Topics item about legislation I am sponsoring in the New Jersey General Assembly to stress sexual abstinence in public schools.</p>
        <p>My bill, A-3306, requires that public schools stress the scientific evidence that abstinence from sexual activity is the only completely reliable method of avoiding the sexual transmission of the acquired immune deficiency syndrome virus and of avoiding pregnancy. It does not, however, prohibit instruction about methods of contraception like condoms.</p>
        <p>Those who oppose the bill use the same argument you employ, that my bill withholds information from the children. Not to teach abstinence, as is the case in some high schools around the state, is withholding the most vital information of all.</p>
        <p>Surgeon General C. Everett Koop and William Bennett, former Education Secretary, have urged stressing abstinence, stating that ''when it comes to AIDS, science and morality teach the same lesson.''</p>
        <p>My bill does not attempt to legislate morality. It stresses the scientific evidence. High schools are sending the wrong message that condoms are completely reliable against AIDS.</p>
        <p>We must educate and protect our future generations if we are to stop the AIDS epidemic. We must provide the proper information - not only contraception but abstinence. My bill simply adds abstinence to what is already being taught. Anything short of this is irresponsible. MARION CRECCO  Assemblywoman, District 30  Trenton, Dec. 7, 1988</p>
      </block>
